 way key Enlightenment thinkers viewed nature. His sophisticated analysis ultimately questions postmodern narratives that have assumed a monolithic Enlightenment—characterized by the dominance of instrumental reason—that has led to many of the disasters of modern life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aSciencexHistoryy18th century. 0aVitalism. 70(DE-601)1043068310(DE-588)4003524-4aAufklärung2gnd 70(DE-601)1062193830(DE-588)4041408-5aNaturphilosophie2gnd 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  a18th century.  aanimism.  acharles louis dumas.  achemistry.  acounter enlightenment.  acuvier.  aearly modern enlightenment.  aenlightenment.  aepigenesis.  ageneration.  ahistory of science.  ahistory.  alife force.  alife science.  amechanism.  amodernity.  anatural history.  anatural philosophy.  anatural world.  anature.  anaturphilosophie.  aphilosophy.  aphysiology.  areason.  arelationship with nature.  areligion and science.  areproduction.  aromanticism.  ascience.  ascientific disciplines.  aspark of life.  astahlian chemistry.  avitalism.  awilliam cullen.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024135040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093100840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520931008423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520931008/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY